HEADWORD: Sinapine
<hw>Sin"a*pine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>sinapi</ets>, <ets>sinapis</ets>, mustard, Gr. <?/<?/<?/: cf. F.
<ets>sinapine</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An alkaloid
occurring in the seeds of mustard. It is extracted, in combination with
sulphocyanic acid, as a white crystalline substance, having a hot,
bitter taste. When sinapine is isolated it is unstable and undergoes
decomposition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

